(train_images, _), (_, _) = tf.keras.datasets.cifar10.load_data()

# Normalize the images to [-1, 1]
train_images = (train_images - 127.5) / 127.5

# Reshape the images
train_images = train_images.reshape(train_images.shape[0], 32, 32, 3)

BUFFER_SIZE = 50000
BATCH_SIZE = 64

# Create a dataset object
train_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices(train_images).shuffle(BUFFER_SIZE).batch(BATCH_SIZE)
print("Loading Dataset Done")

Pre-Processing
In [18]:
# Global Constants
noise_dim = 100
BATCH_SIZE = 64
EPOCHS = 35
seed = tf.random.normal([16, noise_dim])  # For generating images at checkpoints

# Load and preprocess dataset (e.g., CIFAR-10)
def load_data():
    print("Loading and preprocessing dataset...")
    start_time = time.time()
    
    (train_images, _), (_, _) = tf.keras.datasets.cifar10.load_data()
    train_images = train_images / 127.5 - 1.0  # Normalize to [-1, 1]
    train_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices(train_images).shuffle(60000).batch(BATCH_SIZE)
    
    end_time = time.time()
    print(f"Dataset loaded and preprocessed in {end_time - start_time:.2f} seconds.")
    return train_dataset

train_dataset = load_data()

Loading and preprocessing dataset...
Dataset loaded and preprocessed in 4.45 seconds.
Model Building
In [19]:
# Build Generator Model
def build_generator():
    print("Building generator model...")
    model = models.Sequential([
        layers.Input(shape=(noise_dim,)),
        layers.Dense(8 * 8 * 512, use_bias=False),
        layers.BatchNormalization(),
        layers.ReLU(),
        layers.Reshape((8, 8, 512)),
        layers.Conv2DTranspose(256, (5, 5), strides=(1, 1), padding='same', use_bias=False),
        layers.BatchNormalization(),
        layers.ReLU(),
        layers.Conv2DTranspose(128, (5, 5), strides=(2, 2), padding='same', use_bias=False),
        layers.BatchNormalization(),
        layers.ReLU(),
        layers.Conv2DTranspose(64, (5, 5), strides=(2, 2), padding='same', use_bias=False),
        layers.BatchNormalization(),
        layers.ReLU(),
        layers.Conv2DTranspose(3, (5, 5), strides=(1, 1), padding='same', use_bias=False, activation='tanh')
    ])
    print("Generator model built.")
    return model

# Build Discriminator Model
def build_discriminator():
    print("Building discriminator model...")
    model = models.Sequential([
        layers.Input(shape=[32, 32, 3]),
        layers.Conv2D(64, (5, 5), padding='same'),
        layers.LeakyReLU(),
        layers.Dropout(0.3),
        layers.Conv2D(128, (5, 5), strides=(2, 2), padding='same'),
        layers.LeakyReLU(),
        layers.Dropout(0.3),
        layers.Conv2D(256, (5, 5), strides=(2, 2), padding='same'),
        layers.LeakyReLU(),
        layers.Dropout(0.3),
        layers.Flatten(),
        layers.Dense(1)
    ])
    print("Discriminator model built.")
    return model

# Loss Functions
def discriminator_loss(real_output, fake_output):
    return tf.keras.losses.BinaryCrossentropy(from_logits=True)(tf.ones_like(real_output), real_output) + \
           tf.keras.losses.BinaryCrossentropy(from_logits=True)(tf.zeros_like(fake_output), fake_output)

def generator_loss(fake_output):
    return tf.keras.losses.BinaryCrossentropy(from_logits=True)(tf.ones_like(fake_output), fake_output)

# Learning Rate Scheduler
def lr_schedule(epoch):
    initial_lr = 1e-4
    if epoch < 10:
        return initial_lr
    else:
        return initial_lr * tf.math.exp(-0.1 * (epoch - 10))

# Optimizers
generator_optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=lr_schedule(0))
discriminator_optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=lr_schedule(0))
In [20]:
# Training Step
@tf.function
def train_step(images, epoch):
    noise = tf.random.normal([BATCH_SIZE, noise_dim])
    
    with tf.GradientTape() as gen_tape, tf.GradientTape() as disc_tape:
        generated_images = generator(noise, training=True)
        
        real_output = discriminator(images, training=True)
        fake_output = discriminator(generated_images, training=True)
        
        gen_loss = generator_loss(fake_output)
        disc_loss = discriminator_loss(real_output, fake_output)
    
    gradients_of_generator = gen_tape.gradient(gen_loss, generator.trainable_variables)
    gradients_of_discriminator = disc_tape.gradient(disc_loss, discriminator.trainable_variables)
    
    generator_optimizer.learning_rate.assign(lr_schedule(epoch))
    discriminator_optimizer.learning_rate.assign(lr_schedule(epoch))

    generator_optimizer.apply_gradients(zip(gradients_of_generator, generator.trainable_variables))
    discriminator_optimizer.apply_gradients(zip(gradients_of_discriminator, discriminator.trainable_variables))

    return gen_loss, disc_loss

# Generate and Save Images
def generate_and_save_images(model, epoch, test_input):
    print(f"Generating and saving images for epoch {epoch}...")
    start_time = time.time()
    
    predictions = model(test_input, training=False)
    
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(4, 4, figsize=(8, 8))
    fig.suptitle(f'Generated Images at Epoch {epoch}', fontsize=16)

    for i, ax in enumerate(axes.flatten()):
        ax.imshow((predictions[i] + 1) / 2)  # Rescale to [0, 1]
        ax.set_title(f'Image {i + 1}', fontsize=10)
        ax.axis('off')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.9)
    plt.savefig(f'image_at_epoch_{epoch:04d}.png')
    plt.show()
    
    end_time = time.time()
    print(f"Images generated and saved in {end_time - start_time:.2f} seconds.")

# Save Models
def save_models(generator, discriminator, epoch):
    print(f"Saving models for epoch {epoch}...")
    start_time = time.time()
    
    generator.save(f'generator_epoch_{epoch + 1}.keras')
    discriminator.save(f'discriminator_epoch_{epoch + 1}.keras')
    
    end_time = time.time()
    print(f"Models saved in {end_time - start_time:.2f} seconds.")

# Training Loop
def train(dataset, epochs):
    for epoch in range(epochs):
        print(f"\nStarting Epoch {epoch + 1}/{epochs}")
        epoch_start_time = time.time()
        
        gen_loss_epoch = []
        disc_loss_epoch = []
        
        batch_num = 1
        for image_batch in dataset:
            print(f"Processing batch {batch_num} of epoch {epoch + 1}...")
            batch_start_time = time.time()
            
            gen_loss, disc_loss = train_step(image_batch, epoch)
            gen_loss_epoch.append(gen_loss)
            disc_loss_epoch.append(disc_loss)
            
            batch_end_time = time.time()
            print(f"Batch {batch_num} processed in {batch_end_time - batch_start_time:.2f} seconds.")
            batch_num += 1
        
        gen_loss_avg = np.mean(gen_loss_epoch)
        disc_loss_avg = np.mean(disc_loss_epoch)
        print(f'Epoch {epoch + 1}/{epochs} - Generator Loss: {gen_loss_avg:.4f} - Discriminator Loss: {disc_loss_avg:.4f}')
        print(f'Epoch {epoch + 1}/{epochs} - Learning Rates: Generator: {generator_optimizer.learning_rate.numpy():.6f}, Discriminator: {discriminator_optimizer.learning_rate.numpy():.6f}')
        
        generate_and_save_images(generator, epoch + 1, seed)
        save_models(generator, discriminator, epoch)
        
        epoch_end_time = time.time()
        print(f"Epoch {epoch + 1} completed in {epoch_end_time - epoch_start_time:.2f} seconds.")

# Initialize Models
generator = build_generator()
discriminator = build_discriminator()

In [23]:
# Function to generate and display images
def generate_and_save_images(model, epoch, test_input):
    print(f"Generating and saving images for epoch {epoch}...")
    
    predictions = model(test_input, training=False)
    
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(4, 4, figsize=(8, 8))
    fig.suptitle(f'Generated Images at Epoch {epoch}', fontsize=16)

    for i, ax in enumerate(axes.flatten()):
        ax.imshow((predictions[i] + 1) / 2)  # Rescale to [0, 1]
        ax.set_title(f'Image {i + 1}', fontsize=10)
        ax.axis('off')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.9)
    plt.show()

# Evaluate the final generator model
def evaluate_final_generator(generator):
    print("Evaluating final generator model...")
    generate_and_save_images(generator, 'final', seed)

# Assuming your generator model is named 'generator' and is loaded into the environment
evaluate_final_generator(generator)

OOV_TOKEN = "<OOV>"

tokenizer = Tokenizer(num_words=VOCAB_SIZE, oov_token=OOV_TOKEN)
tokenizer.fit_on_texts([text.numpy().decode('utf-8') for text, label in train_dataset])

def tokenize_data(data):
    sequences = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences([text.numpy().decode('utf-8') for text, label in data])
    padded_sequences = pad_sequences(sequences, maxlen=MAX_LENGTH, truncating=TRUNC_TYPE)
    labels = [label.numpy() for _, label in data]
    return padded_sequences, labels

X_train, y_train = tokenize_data(train_dataset)
X_test, y_test = tokenize_data(test_dataset)

# Convert labels to numpy arrays
y_train = tf.keras.utils.to_categorical(y_train, num_classes=2)
y_test = tf.keras.utils.to_categorical(y_test, num_classes=2)
Building Models
In [8]:
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Embedding, LSTM, GRU, SimpleRNN, Dense, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential

# Embedding layer
embedding_layer = Embedding(VOCAB_SIZE, EMBEDDING_DIM)

def create_lstm_model():
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(embedding_layer)
    model.add(LSTM(128, return_sequences=True))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(LSTM(128))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(Dense(2, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    model.summary()
    return model

def create_gru_model():
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(embedding_layer)
    model.add(GRU(128, return_sequences=True))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(GRU(128))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(Dense(2, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    model.summary()
    return model

def create_simple_rnn_model():
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(embedding_layer)
    model.add(SimpleRNN(128, return_sequences=True))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(SimpleRNN(128))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(Dense(2, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    model.summary()
    return model
In [11]:
lstm_model = create_lstm_model()
gru_model = create_gru_model()
simple_rnn_model = create_simple_rnn_model()

Predictions
In [24]:
import pandas as pd

y_pred_lstm = lstm_model.predict(X_test)
y_pred_gru = gru_model.predict(X_test)
y_pred_simple_rnn = simple_rnn_model.predict(X_test)

# Convert to class labels
y_pred_lstm_classes = tf.argmax(y_pred_lstm, axis=1).numpy()
y_pred_gru_classes = tf.argmax(y_pred_gru, axis=1).numpy()
y_pred_simple_rnn_classes = tf.argmax(y_pred_simple_rnn, axis=1).numpy()

# Actual labels
y_test_classes = tf.argmax(y_test, axis=1).numpy()

# Create a DataFrame to store the results
results_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Actual Labels': y_test_classes,
    'LSTM Model Predictions': y_pred_lstm_classes,
    'GRU Model Predictions': y_pred_gru_classes,
    'Simple RNN Model Predictions': y_pred_simple_rnn_classes
})

# Ensemble by averaging probabilities (Soft Voting)
y_pred_ensemble = (y_pred_lstm + y_pred_gru) / 2

# Convert to class labels
y_pred_ensemble_classes = tf.argmax(y_pred_ensemble, axis=1).numpy()

# Add ensemble results to the DataFrame
results_df['Ensemble Model Predictions'] = y_pred_ensemble_classes

# Evaluate individual models
lstm_accuracy = tf.reduce_mean(tf.cast(tf.equal(y_test_classes, y_pred_lstm_classes), tf.float32))
gru_accuracy = tf.reduce_mean(tf.cast(tf.equal(y_test_classes, y_pred_gru_classes), tf.float32))
simple_rnn_accuracy = tf.reduce_mean(tf.cast(tf.equal(y_test_classes, y_pred_simple_rnn_classes), tf.float32))
ensemble_accuracy = tf.reduce_mean(tf.cast(tf.equal(y_test_classes, y_pred_ensemble_classes), tf.float32))

# Add accuracy scores to the DataFrame
accuracy_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Model': ['LSTM', 'GRU', 'Simple RNN', 'Ensemble'],
    'Accuracy': [lstm_accuracy.numpy(), gru_accuracy.numpy(), simple_rnn_accuracy.numpy(), ensemble_accuracy.numpy()]
})

In [16]:
# Remove users with less than 200 ratings and books with less than 100 ratings to reduce the dataset size
print("Filtering data...")
ratings_count = ratings.groupby('User-ID').size()
ratings_filtered = ratings[ratings['User-ID'].isin(ratings_count[ratings_count >= 200].index)]

books_count = ratings.groupby('ISBN').size()
ratings_filtered = ratings_filtered[ratings_filtered['ISBN'].isin(books_count[books_count >= 100].index)]

print("Data filtered successfully!")
print(f"Number of remaining users: {ratings_filtered['User-ID'].nunique()}")
print(f"Number of remaining books: {ratings_filtered['ISBN'].nunique()}")

# Merge datasets for further analysis
print("Merging datasets...")
ratings_merged = pd.merge(ratings_filtered, books, on='ISBN')
print("Datasets merged successfully!")

# Function to recommend books with detailed output and plots
def recommend_books(user_id, top_n=10):
    print(f"Generating recommendations for user {user_id}...")
    
    # Predict ratings for all books for the given user
    all_books = books['ISBN'].unique()
    predictions = [svd.predict(user_id, book_id) for book_id in all_books]
    
    # Sort predictions by estimated rating
    sorted_predictions = sorted(predictions, key=lambda x: x.est, reverse=True)
    
    # Get top N recommendations
    top_predictions = sorted_predictions[:top_n]
    top_book_ids = [pred.iid for pred in top_predictions]
    
    # Fetch book details
    recommended_books = books[books['ISBN'].isin(top_book_ids)]
    
    # Prepare data for plotting
    recommendations_df = pd.DataFrame({
        'ISBN': [pred.iid for pred in top_predictions],
        'Estimated Rating': [pred.est for pred in top_predictions]
    }).merge(recommended_books, on='ISBN')
    
    # Print recommendations in tabular format
    print(f"\nRecommended books for user {user_id}:")
    print(recommendations_df[['Book-Title', 'ISBN', 'Book-Author', 'Year-Of-Publication', 'Estimated Rating']])
    
    # Plotting
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))

    # Bar plot of top N recommended books
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    sns.barplot(data=recommendations_df, y='Book-Title', x='Estimated Rating', hue='Book-Title', orient='h', legend=False)
    plt.title('Top N Recommended Books')
    plt.xlabel('Estimated Rating')
    plt.ylabel('Book Title')

    # Histogram of estimated ratings
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    sns.histplot(recommendations_df['Estimated Rating'], bins=10, kde=True, color='blue')
    plt.title('Distribution of Estimated Ratings')
    plt.xlabel('Estimated Rating')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
    return recommendations_df

# Function to get user input and provide recommendations interactively
def interactive_recommendations():
    user_id = input("Enter your user ID: ")
    try:
        user_id = int(user_id)  # Ensure user ID is treated as integer
        print(f"Fetching recommendations for user {user_id}...")
        recommendations = recommend_books(user_id)
        if recommendations.empty:
            print("No recommendations available for this user.")
        else:
            print(f"\nRecommended books for user {user_id}:")
            print(recommendations[['Book-Title', 'ISBN', 'Book-Author', 'Year-Of-Publication', 'Estimated Rating']])
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"An error occurred: {e}")

# Run interactive recommendations
interactive_recommendations()

# Define Neural Network for Policy Network
class PolicyNet(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(PolicyNet, self).__init__()
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(4, 64)  # Adjust input size based on state dimension
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(64, 2)  # Adjust output size based on action dimension
    
    def forward(self, x):
        x = torch.relu(self.fc1(x))
        x = self.fc2(x)
        return x

# Initialize policy and target networks
policy_net = PolicyNet()
target_net = PolicyNet()
target_net.load_state_dict(policy_net.state_dict())  # Initialize target_net with policy_net weights

# Optimizer
optimizer = optim.Adam(policy_net.parameters(), lr=0.001)

# Hyperparameters
memory = deque(maxlen=10000)
epsilon = 1.0
epsilon_decay = 0.995
min_epsilon = 0.01
episode_limit = 1000
target_update_delay = 10
test_delay = 50

# Initialize log DataFrame
episode_logs = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Episode', 'Score', 'Reward', 'Steps'])

# Define the environment (mock example, replace with actual environment)
class MockEnv:
    def reset(self):
        return np.zeros(4)  # Adjust state dimension
    
    def step(self, action):
        next_state = np.zeros(4)  # Adjust state dimension
        reward = np.random.random()  # Example reward
        done = np.random.rand() > 0.95  # Example done condition
        return next_state, reward, done, {}

env = MockEnv()

# Define action selection
def get_action(state, epsilon):
    if np.random.rand() < epsilon:
        return np.random.choice([0, 1])  # Adjust action space
    else:
        state_tensor = torch.FloatTensor(state).unsqueeze(0)
        with torch.no_grad():
            return policy_net(state_tensor).argmax().item()

def normalize_state(state):
    state = np.array(state)
    max_abs = np.max(np.abs(state))
    if max_abs == 0:
        return state  # Or some other handling strategy
    return state / max_abs

# Define model optimization
def optimize_model(batch_size):
    if len(memory) < batch_size:
        return

    # Sample a batch of experiences from memory
    train_sample = random.sample(memory, batch_size)
    
    # Convert list of numpy arrays to single numpy array
    state_batch = np.array([s[0] for s in train_sample])
    action_batch = np.array([s[1] for s in train_sample])
    reward_batch = np.array([s[2] for s in train_sample])
    next_state_batch = np.array([s[3] for s in train_sample])
    
    # Convert numpy arrays to tensors
    state = torch.tensor(state_batch, dtype=torch.float32)
    next_state = torch.tensor(next_state_batch, dtype=torch.float32)
    action = torch.tensor(action_batch, dtype=torch.int64)
    reward = torch.tensor(reward_batch, dtype=torch.float32)

    # Perform optimization
    q_estimates = policy_net(state).detach()
    next_state_q_estimates = target_net(next_state).detach()
    next_actions = policy_net(next_state).argmax(dim=1)
Functions For Training & Evaluation
In [2]:
def train_one_episode(episode_number):
    global epsilon
    current_state = env.reset()
    current_state = normalize_state(current_state)
    done = False
    score = 0
    reward = 0
    step_count = 0
    
    while not done:
        action = get_action(current_state, epsilon)
        next_state, env_reward, done, _ = env.step(action)
        next_state = normalize_state(next_state)
        memory.append((current_state, action, env_reward, next_state))
        current_state = next_state
        score += env_reward
        reward += env_reward
        step_count += 1

        optimize_model(100)

        epsilon -= epsilon_decay
        epsilon = max(epsilon, min_epsilon)

    episode_logs.loc[episode_number] = [episode_number, score, reward, step_count]
    print(f'Episode {episode_number + 1} finished with score: {score}, reward: {reward}, steps: {step_count}')
    return score, reward

# Testing function
def test():
    # Example test function
    # Replace with actual testing logic
    test_score = np.random.random()
    test_reward = np.random.random()
    return test_score, test_reward

# Plotting training progress
def plot_training_progress():
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))

    plt.subplot(3, 1, 1)
    plt.plot(episode_logs['Episode'], episode_logs['Score'], label='Score', color='blue')
    plt.xlabel('Episode')
    plt.ylabel('Score')
    plt.title('Episode Scores')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)

    plt.subplot(3, 1, 2)
    plt.plot(episode_logs['Episode'], episode_logs['Reward'], label='Reward', color='orange')
    plt.xlabel('Episode')
    plt.ylabel('Reward')
    plt.title('Episode Rewards')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)

    plt.subplot(3, 1, 3)
    plt.plot(episode_logs['Episode'], episode_logs['Steps'], label='Steps', color='green')
    plt.xlabel('Episode')
    plt.ylabel('Steps')
    plt.title('Episode Steps')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
Main Function Calling
In [ ]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
# Main training loop
def main():
    best_test_reward = 0

    for i in range(episode_limit):
        score, reward = train_one_episode(i)
        print(f'Episode {i + 1}: score: {score} - reward: {reward}')

        if i % target_update_delay == 0:
            target_net.load_state_dict(policy_net.state_dict())
            target_net.eval()

        if (i + 1) % test_delay == 0:
            test_score, test_reward = test()
            print(f'Test Episode {i + 1}: test score: {test_score} - test reward: {test_reward}')
            if test_reward > best_test_reward:
                print('New best test reward. Saving model')
                best_test_reward = test_reward
                torch.save(policy_net.state_dict(), 'policy_net.pth')

    if episode_limit % test_delay != 0:
        test_score, test_reward = test()
        print(f'Test Episode {episode_limit}: test score: {test_score} - test reward: {test_reward}')
        if test_reward > best_test_reward:
            print('New best test reward. Saving model')
            best_test_reward = test_reward
            torch.save(policy_net.state_dict(), 'policy_net.pth')

    print(f'Best test reward: {best_test_reward}')
    plot_training_progress()

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
